From 70f46fb783c46418b191406c7279e728ff8f4416 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Mykola Lysenko <nickolay.lysenko@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 12 Jul 2026 16:02:38 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 1/5] btrfs/081: suppress bash wait diagnostics for the reaped
 reader pid

The test kills its background reader-loop subshell and then waits for
it.  With bash >= 5.2 the subshell may already have been reaped, and
wait prints "wait_for: No record of process <pid>" to stderr.  That
line lands in the test output and fails the golden output comparison
even though the actual verification (the md5 comparison of the cloned
files) passed.

Discard wait's stderr; its exit status is not consumed and the test's
correctness signal is the md5 output.

Observed as an intermittent failure on btrfs test runs with bash 5.2
(Ubuntu 24.04).

Signed-off-by: Mykola Lysenko <nickolay.lysenko@gmail.com>
---
 tests/btrfs/081 | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/tests/btrfs/081 b/tests/btrfs/081
index 35db6dd..040f18d 100755
--- a/tests/btrfs/081
+++ b/tests/btrfs/081
@@ -81,7 +81,7 @@ $CLONER_PROG -s 0 -d 0 -l $(($num_extents * $extent_size)) \
 	$SCRATCH_MNT/foo $SCRATCH_MNT/bar
 
 kill $reader_pid > /dev/null 2>&1
-wait $reader_pid
+wait $reader_pid 2>/dev/null
 
 # Now both foo and bar should have exactly the same content.
 # This didn't use to be the case before the btrfs kernel fix mentioned
